	<div class="container">
		<div class="stage-header">
			<div>
				<p class="section-label">Stage Two</p>
				<h1 class="section-title">The Investigative Cycle</h1>
			</div>
		</div>
		<p class="section-intro">
			Once you've been referred and seen by a fertility specialist, the investigative cycle 
			begins. This is the phase where your medical team runs tests to identify potential causes. 
			Nobody tells you in advance what this actually looks like day-to-day, so here's what to expect.
		</p>

		<%- include('partials/stage2-zigzag') %>
	</div>
</section>

<section class="section-light">
	<div class="container">

		<div class="info-block">
			<div class="text-center my-3">
				<img src="/fertility-v2/static/images/percentage_maker.png" alt="Image Explain-Infertility is not just a 
				female issue. About 30% of cases are due to male factors, 40% to female factors, and the 
				remaining 30% involve a combination of both or remain unexplained." style="width: 100%;">
			</div>

			<h4>Common Tests & What They're For During the Investigative Cycle</h4>
			<div class="timeline">
				<div class="timeline-item">
					<h5>Cycle Day 3</h5>
					<p>
						This is your first and busiest clinic visit. Expect to be there for a while 
						as multiple tests are done on the same day.
					</p>
					<strong>Screening Blood Work + Hormone Panel</strong>
					<p>
						Around 6 vials of blood covering various blood levels, immunities, hepatitis, and 
						infectious disease testing including HIV. At the same time, your hormone panel will 
						be drawn to assess ovarian function, thyroid health, and hormonal balance. <br><br>
						This typically includes FSH (Follicle Stimulating Hormone), LH (Luteinizing Hormone), 
						Estradiol, TSH (Thyroid Stimulating Hormone), and Prolactin. All covered by 
						<span class="ohip-tip" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="OHIP (Ontario Health Insurance Plan) 
						is Ontario's publicly funded health insurance, available to eligible Ontario residents 
						at no cost.">OHIP</span>.
					</p>
					<strong>Baseline Ultrasound</strong>
					<p>
						You will need a full bladder for this appointment. The ultrasound includes both 
						external (abdominal) and internal (transvaginal) imaging. Your doctor will check 
						your antral follicle count, uterine lining, and look for any structural abnormalities 
						like fibroids or cysts. An additional 1 tube of blood may also be drawn. Covered by 
						<span class="ohip-tip" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="OHIP (Ontario Health Insurance Plan) 
						is Ontario's publicly funded health insurance, available to eligible Ontario residents 
						at no cost.">OHIP</span>.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div class="timeline-item">
					<h5>Cycle Day 5 to 11: Sono (Sonohysterogram)</h5>
					<p>
						Saline is injected into the uterus while an internal ultrasound is performed to 
						check for structural abnormalities such as polyps, fibroids, or other uterine issues. 
						This test needs to be scheduled within a specific window of your cycle. You will likely 
						be advised to take 2 over-the-counter pain relievers about an hour before your appointment 
						to help with discomfort. Covered by 
						<span class="ohip-tip" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="OHIP (Ontario Health Insurance Plan) 
						is Ontario's publicly funded health insurance, available to eligible Ontario residents 
						at no cost.">OHIP</span>.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div class="timeline-item">
					<h5>Cycle Day 10 to 18: Cycle Monitoring</h5>
					<p>
						Starting around day 10, you will visit the clinic every other day for an internal 
						(transvaginal) ultrasound and blood work. Your medical team is monitoring the hormones 
						involved in follicle development to pinpoint the time of ovulation. The number of visits 
						varies from person to person, and your nurse will let you know when to come back each time. 
						Covered by 
						<span class="ohip-tip" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="OHIP (Ontario Health Insurance Plan) 
						is Ontario's publicly funded health insurance, available to eligible Ontario residents 
						at no cost.">OHIP</span>.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div class="timeline-item">
					<h5>Around Cycle Day 20: P4 / Progesterone</h5>
					<p>
						One vial of blood to confirm whether ovulation has occurred. Due to varying individual 
						cycle lengths, your nurse will confirm the specific date it should be drawn. Covered by 
						<span class="ohip-tip" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="OHIP (Ontario Health Insurance Plan) 
						is Ontario's publicly funded health insurance, available to eligible Ontario residents 
						at no cost.">OHIP</span>.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div class="timeline-item">
					<h5>Around Cycle Day 28: Beta HCG / Pregnancy Test</h5>
					<p>
						One vial of blood to confirm your level of Beta HCG. Due to varying individual cycle 
						lengths, your nurse will confirm the specific date it should be drawn. Covered by 
						<span class="ohip-tip" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="OHIP (Ontario Health Insurance Plan) 
						is Ontario's publicly funded health insurance, available to eligible Ontario residents 
						at no cost.">OHIP</span>.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div class="timeline-item">
					<h5>Any Day: AMH (Anti-Müllerian Hormone)</h5>
					<p>
						A single vial of blood that measures your ovarian reserve. Can be drawn on any day of 
						your cycle. Not covered by 
						<span class="ohip-tip" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="OHIP (Ontario Health Insurance Plan) 
						is Ontario's publicly funded health insurance, available to eligible Ontario residents 
						at no cost.">OHIP</span>. Cost: approximately $105.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div class="timeline-item">
					<h5>Any Day: Vitamin D</h5>
					<p>
						A blood test to check your vitamin D levels, since low vitamin D may negatively affect 
						fertility outcomes. Not covered by 
						<span class="ohip-tip" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="OHIP (Ontario Health Insurance Plan) 
						is Ontario's publicly funded health insurance, available to eligible Ontario residents 
						at no cost.">OHIP</span>. Cost: approximately $65.138.197.19.64
					</p>
				</div>

				<div class="timeline-item">
					<h5>By Appointment: Comprehensive Semen Analysis with Strict Morphology</h5>
					<p>
						If you have a male partner, they will need to provide a semen sample for analysis. 
						This test evaluates sperm count, motility, and morphology (shape) using strict criteria. 
						Your partner will need to abstain for at least 3 days before the test, and an appointment 
						must be booked in advance.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div class="timeline-item">
					<h5>After Day 21: Review Appointment</h5>
					<p>
						Only after completing your first investigative cycle and all required testing, you will 
						be asked to book a review appointment with your doctor. This should be scheduled after 
						day 21 and before your next period. During this appointment, your doctor will go over 
						your results, determine your type of infertility, and create a plan for your next treatment 
						cycle. The review can be done through an online video call or in person at the clinic.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>

		<div class="highlight-box">
			<strong>Why does this take so long?</strong> Not all tests can be done in the same cycle. Some are 
			time-sensitive (e.g., blood work on day 3, Sono mid-cycle). If scheduling doesn't align, you may wait 
			another month. This is normal but frustrating, and it's why knowing the timeline upfront helps manage expectations.
		</div>

		<div class="info-block">
			<h4>Possible Diagnoses After Investigation</h4>
			<p>After completing the investigative cycle, your specialist may identify one or more of the following:</p>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Ovulation disorders</strong> such as PCOS (Polycystic Ovary Syndrome)</li>
				<li><strong>Hormonal imbalance</strong> such as thyroid issues or elevated prolactin</li>
				<li><strong>Tubal blockage or damage</strong></li>
				<li><strong>Uterine structural issues</strong> such as polyps or fibroids</li>
				<li><strong>Endometriosis</strong></li>
				<li><strong>Low ovarian reserve</strong> often age-related</li>
				<li><strong>Male factor</strong> sperm quality issues</li>
				<li><strong>Unexplained infertility</strong> all tests come back normal, no identifiable cause</li>
			</ul>
			<p class="mt-2">Your diagnosis will determine which treatment path your doctor recommends. In some cases, multiple factors may be identified.</p>
		</div>

		<div class="cost-box">
			<strong>Cost note:</strong> Most blood work and ultrasounds during the investigative cycle are covered by 
			<span class="ohip-tip" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="OHIP (Ontario Health Insurance Plan) 
			is Ontario's publicly funded health insurance, available to eligible Ontario residents 
			at no cost.">OHIP</span>. However, some tests like AMH ($105) and Vitamin D ($65) are not covered. 
			Ask your clinic upfront for a full fee schedule.
		</div>

		<div class="d-flex justify-content-between mt-5">
